<h3><b>Short Description</b></h3><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal">If you set this variable to TRUE, the monitor agent starts
preserving the values of monitored objects and session variables. <o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal">When you disable or deploy a newer version of measurement
threshold policy, the policies are removed from the opcmona memory and the
values of monitored objects and session variables of the existing running
policies are also removed. The new policy version is then loaded and opcmona
will store new values for the monitored objects and session variables.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal">If you set this variable to FALSE, the monitor agent stops
preserving the values of monitored objects and session variables. <o:p></o:p></p>

<h3><b>Long Description</b></h3><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal">This configuration variable decide whether to preserve the
values of monitored objects and session variables for opcmona. If it preserve
the values, opcmona can get these values even after it restarts.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal">For example, let’s assume there is a Monitoring threshold
policy with threshold 10.<o:p></o:p></p><h2>OPC_MON_KEEP_PERSISTENT_PERL_ENGINE</h2><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p><table class="MsoTableGrid" border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="0" style="border-left: none;">
